06:30.146 --> 06:56.434
Now, as he ends there in verse 17, having said that suffering and glory are not to be considered apart from each other, you will notice he goes on now to say that suffering and the reality of experiencing it is such that what it leads to is far greater than the suffering itself.

06:56.674 --> 07:06.826
The glory that we will one day experience then is far outweighs the suffering that we experience now.

07:06.866 --> 07:15.255
And this is of course, I think, hard for those of us who live in the context in which most of us live.

07:17.418 --> 07:21.362
For the first in a little while, perhaps, with the wind blowing

07:21.634 --> 07:26.400
pretty fiercely against our faces if we want to hold to Christian conviction.

07:27.041 --> 07:45.746
We've got at least an inkling of what Peter was on about when he writes to the folks who are the scattered believers in the early century, and he says, you know, you've been born again to a living hope by the resurrection of Jesus Christ from the dead, and now you suffer, and even if that is for a little while.

07:46.306 --> 07:50.011
